Gamma rays from capture and fission were measured
simultaneously. Capture spectrum was corrected for
contribution of prompt fission gamma rays. Final
result is weighted averaged value of two measurements.
Gamma rays were measured using 4 Pi highly
segmented highly efficient gamma-ray calorimeter
DANCE. It consists of 160 BaF2 scintillation crystals,
and each one has the same solid-angle coverage. The
calorimeter has inner radius of 17 cm and each
crystal has length of 15 cm.
Parallel plate avalanche counter was used to
detect fission fragments and tag the gamma rays from
fission.
Experiment performed at Lujan Neutron
Scattering Center of LANSCE using the DANCE array
Pulsed neutron beam was produced via
spallation on a natural W target by an 800-MeV proton
linear accelerator beam. The average proton beam
current at the spallation target was about 1 - 2
mu-A. The neutron beam structure contained 625 mu-s
long 'macropulses' driven by two of every three such
macropulses from the accelerator for an average rate
of 40/s. Each macropulse consisted of 'micropulses'
spaced every 1.8 mu-s, each <1 ns long. The pulsed
beam allowed incident neutron energies to be
determined using the time-of-flight technique.
neutron energy determined by time of flight
method, measured by the time difference between the
beam pulse and the event detected by either DANCE or
PPAC. Two measurements were made using target with
total mass of 395 mu-g. In the second experiment target
with total mass of 374 mu-g was inserted into PPAC,
which was used in an attempt to measure neutron-induced
fission of 238Pu, which proved to be difficult.
Absolute scale of the cross section was determined
according to the 234U resonance at 5.16 eV, with
integrated cross section between 4.91-5.38 eV
of 2640 beV
238Pu was fabricated at LLNL by using electroplating
cell. The target material was deposited over an area
of  approx. 7 mm in diameter on both sides of the
titanium foil with a thickness of 3 mu-m. Sample
contained also
239Pu - 0.30% relative to 238Pu
240Pu - 0.34% relative to 238Pu
234U is daughter nucleus of 238Pu
Two samples with total mass of 395 and 374 mu-g were
used
Statistical uncertainty
Systematic uncertainty
The systematic uncertainty is estimated to about 5%
for En below 1 eV attributed to the uncertainty of
the neutron flux measurement
The systematic uncertainty is estimated to about 30%
for En above 10 keV attributed to the uncertainty of
the background subtraction.
It is better than 3% for En between 1 eV and 1 keV
and better than 10% for En between 1 and 10 keV.
